{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778218595,"nonce":"z9Vo+/eh2IQ6PrR4NxuMuzwjuVM=","title":"RunPod operational lessons (env stability, parallel-process GPU, SSH/monitoring, lifecycle)","message":"Consolidates operational knowledge for spinning up, configuring, and running rlrmp experiments on RunPod cloud pods. **Subset already in `CLAUDE.md`'s \"RunPod Deploy Runbook\" section** — that runbook is the canonical reference; this issue adds lessons not yet captured there. Surfaced from a 9-process flavor-B training sweep on a 5090 (issue `c723082`).\n\nWhere the runbook is silent or wrong, the runbook should be updated; file follow-up issues per the **Memory Files vs Workflow Instructions** convention.\n\n## Already in `CLAUDE.md` (canonical reference: \"RunPod Deploy Runbook for rlrmp Experiments\")\n\nPod creation flow (image, GPU, DC); path-dep rsync + sed patches for `feedbax` and `jax-cookbook`; `nohup` pattern for installs surviving SSH disconnect; smoke-test command; monitoring cadence; cost discipline (billing on creation); 5090 image requirement (`runpod/pytorch:1.0.3-cu1281-torch290-ubuntu2204` or newer); ask-before-upgrading-tier rule.\n\n---\n\n## Lessons NOT yet in `CLAUDE.md`\n\n### A. JAX environment stability\n\n**A1. `uv sync` overwrites CUDA jaxlib.** After the runbook's post-sync `uv pip install -U \"jax[cuda12]\"` step, the lockfile-pinned `jaxlib` is CPU-only. Re-running `uv sync` (e.g. `uv sync --frozen` for a \"consistency check\") removes the CUDA jaxlib and falls back to CPU. **Never run `uv sync` after the post-sync `jax[cuda12]` install.** Symptoms after regression: `jax.devices()` returns `[CpuDevice(id=0)]` and a warning `An NVIDIA GPU may be present on this machine, but a CUDA-enabled jaxlib is not installed. Falling back to cpu.`\n\n**A2. `uv run` triggers implicit sync by default — bad for parallel processes.** When N processes invoke `uv run python ...` simultaneously on a shared venv, they race on resync (one process re-builds the env while another tries to import). Use `uv run --no-sync python ...` for all parallel invocations after a one-time pre-sync.\n\n**A3. `jaxlib` vs `jax-cuda12-plugin` version-mismatch warning is benign IF `jax.devices()` shows `CudaDevice`.** The warning `JAX plugin jax_cuda12_plugin version X is installed, but it is not compatible with the installed jaxlib version Y, so it will not be used.` doesn't necessarily mean GPU is broken — `jaxlib` 0.9.x has bundled CUDA support that works without the separate plugin. Always verify with `python -c \"import jax; print(jax.devices())\"`.\n\n**A4. End-to-end GPU verification BEFORE launching parallel runs.** A passing matmul (`jnp.ones((4096,4096)) @ jnp.ones(...)`) doesn't guarantee cuDNN works. Add a `lax.conv_general_dilated` test as a cuDNN exercise. The fast smoke-path: ~3 lines, ~5 seconds.\n\n### B. Multi-process GPU (parallel runs on one pod)\n\n**B1. `XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_PREALLOCATE=false` is mandatory for parallel processes.** Default XLA pre-allocates ~75% of device memory at first allocation. With N concurrent processes, the first grabs ~24 GB on a 32 GB 5090; the rest hit `RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED: CUDA_ERROR_OUT_OF_MEMORY` immediately. With pre-allocate disabled, processes use only what they need and N can co-exist comfortably. Set per-process: `XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_PREALLOCATE=false uv run --no-sync python ...`.\n\n**B2. Stagger launches ~10 s apart.** Without stagger, simultaneous JAX inits race on cuDNN handle setup, producing `JaxRuntimeError: INTERNAL: RET_CHECK failure (gpu_compiler.cc:NNNN) dnn_support != nullptr` in N-1 of N processes. Sleep between launches in the launch loop.\n\n### C. SSH and monitoring\n\n**C1. `ConnectTimeout=10` is too aggressive while pod is busy.** During heavy compute (JIT compile, multi-process launch), pod's SSH daemon can't complete handshake in 10 s. Use `ConnectTimeout=30` and add `ServerAliveInterval=60` for long-running connections. Below 30 s, transient timeouts will fool monitoring loops into reporting `SSH_FAIL` even when pod is fully alive.\n\n**C2. zsh does NOT word-split unquoted variables — bash does.** `SSH=\"ssh -i ... root@...\"` then `\\$SSH 'cmd'` works in bash but fails in zsh with \\\"no such file or directory: ssh -i ... root@...\\\" (treated as one literal command name). The Bash tool runs zsh on macOS by default. Mitigation: wrap loops in `bash -c '...'`, use `\\${=SSH}` to force splitting, or inline the SSH command.\n\n**C3. Sentinel files for completion polling, not process state.** `ps aux | grep` undercounts during process forking and overcounts shell wrappers. The reliable signal: each process writes `\\${OUTDIR}/done.sentinel` on success. Polling loop checks `ls done.sentinel | wc -l` against expected count.\n\n**C4. Recurring-poll loop pattern.** For \"wait until job N completes\": background `until`-loop that SSHs every M minutes, exits on sentinel-count target / error pattern in logs / persistent SSH failure. Single notification on completion. Tolerate 5 consecutive transient SSH failures before bailing.\n\n### D. Script \u0026 flag drift\n\n**D1. CLI flags drift between branches; check `--help` after upstream merges.** During this session, `train_minimax.py --n-replicates 5` (used by Part 2.5 baselines) was rejected as `unrecognized arguments`. Replication is now hardcoded to `5` in the `n_replicates` field of the script's default config dict (`scripts/train_minimax.py:282`). Always re-verify CLI flags after a merge train rather than trusting old runbook examples.\n\n**D2. Validation-loss reports may be phase-specific.** `train_minimax.py` logs `Mean validation loss` only during warmup; in the adversarial phase it logs `Adversarial batch X/N — ctrl_loss=...`. A stale `n_val=21` count is the **frozen final warmup checkpoint**, not \"still in warmup.\" Always grep the log for the actual phase markers before drawing conclusions about progress.\n\n### E. Pod lifecycle and cost\n\n**E1. Stop ≠ Terminate.** `runpodctl pod stop \u003cid\u003e` pauses compute, retains storage (storage-only billing). `runpodctl remove pod \u003cid\u003e` deletes the pod entirely. Use `stop` when you'll resume; use `remove` when finished.\n\n**E2. Verify Docker image exists BEFORE \\`pod create\\`.** RunPod templates can reference deleted images; pod creation succeeds but containers fail silently with `manifest unknown` in the web console. Burned ~\\$0.21 in this session on three stuck pods before the user pointed at the web console error. Always `curl` the Docker Hub manifest first.\n\n**E3. Verify `uptimeSeconds \u003e 0` within ~2 min of creation.** Pod billing starts at creation, not container start. Stuck pods burn money. Bail and recreate if uptime stays at 0 past the 2-min mark.\n\n### F. Things to remember about coordination\n\n**F1. Pin Reaper before spawning background subagents** — only when running in a Zellij/tmux pane (otherwise `reaper-pin.sh` exits with \"Not in a supported multiplexer pane\" and pin is unnecessary because the Reaper isn't watching).\n\n**F2. Don't probe-by-error for tool schemas.** If a deferred tool's schema is unknown (e.g. `RemoteTrigger`), look it up rather than iterate ~5 calls each surfacing one missing-field error. Each iteration costs a turn.\n\n---\n\n## Suggested follow-ups\n- Update `CLAUDE.md`'s \"RunPod Deploy Runbook\" with §A1, §A2, §B1, §B2, §C1, §C3 (most load-bearing additions) — or file a separate dotfiles-side issue per the **Memory Files vs Workflow Instructions** convention.\n- File on `1d9ae6f` (rlrmp meta cross-project coord) cross-referencing this issue, since some lessons (esp. C2 zsh word-splitting) generalise beyond rlrmp.","files":null}]}